# Day 2 — Recursion

Today I learned recursion. Honestly when I first heard the word
I thought it was going to be very complicated. But once I understood
the core idea it was simpler than I expected.

---

## What is Recursion

Recursion is when a function calls itself to solve a smaller version
of the same problem.

## The Two Things Every Recursive Function Must Have

1. Base case — this tells the function when to stop
2. Recursive case — this calls the function again with a smaller input

If you forget the base case the function calls itself forever and
you get a RecursionError. I learned this the hard way today.

---

## Understanding Through Factorial

Factorial of n means multiply all numbers from n down to 1.
factorial(4) = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24

### Code

```python
def factorial(n):
    if n == 0:                    # base case — stop here
        return 1
    return n * factorial(n - 1)  # recursive case — smaller input
```

### How I traced it manually
factorial(4)
└── 4 × factorial(3)
└── 3 × factorial(2)
└── 2 × factorial(1)
└── 1 × factorial(0)
└── returns 1  ← base case hit
← returns 1 × 1 = 1
← returns 2 × 1 = 2
← returns 3 × 2 = 6
← returns 4 × 6 = 24

There are two phases happening here. First the function keeps going
down building up the call stack. Then once the base case is hit
the answers start coming back up one by one.

### Complexity

Time  : O(n) — function calls itself n times  
Space : O(n) — n frames sitting on the call stack at the same time

This was the part that surprised me. Even though I am not creating
any new array or list, recursion still uses O(n) space because
every function call sits in memory until it gets its answer back.

